  <h1>How Severance Pay Is Taxed</h1>
  <p class="byline">By <strong>Sloan Whitfield, SHRM-CP</strong> &mdash; Editor-in-Chief &amp; Separation Agreements Lead. Updated May 2026.</p>

  <p>
    Severance pay is taxed as ordinary income. There's no special lower rate for money received when you lose a job. That said, the mechanics of how it's withheld — and the timing of when you receive it — can have a meaningful impact on your actual tax bill. Here's what you need to know.
  </p>

  <h2>Federal Income Tax: Ordinary Rates Apply</h2>
  <p>
    The IRS treats severance as wages, which means it is subject to federal income tax at your ordinary marginal rate. If you're in the 22% bracket and receive $40,000 in severance, you'll owe approximately $8,800 in federal income tax — plus Social Security and Medicare taxes — on that amount.
  </p>
  <p>
    The key variable is <em>how</em> your employer withholds. If your employer treats severance as "supplemental wages" (a common practice), they have two withholding options:
  </p>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Flat rate method:</strong> Withhold at the IRS supplemental wage rate of 22% (for amounts under $1 million). This is the most common approach.</li>
    <li><strong>Aggregate method:</strong> Add the severance to your regular wages and calculate withholding based on your total compensation for the pay period. This can result in higher withholding, especially if you received a large regular paycheck in the same period.</li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    The 22% flat rate is lower than the top marginal rates (32%, 35%, 37%), so high earners who receive severance withheld at 22% may owe a significant additional tax balance when they file. Conversely, lower earners in the 12% bracket may have <em>over</em>withheld and receive a refund.
  </p>

  <h2>FICA Taxes: Social Security and Medicare</h2>
  <p>
    In addition to income tax, severance is subject to FICA taxes:
  </p>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Social Security:</strong> 6.2% on earnings up to the annual wage base ($176,100 in 2025). If you've already hit the wage base earlier in the year with your regular pay, severance may not be subject to Social Security tax.</li>
    <li><strong>Medicare:</strong> 1.45% on all wages, with an additional 0.9% surtax on wages above $200,000 (single) or $250,000 (married filing jointly).</li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    Your employer pays a matching amount for FICA on your behalf. These taxes are not a consideration for planning purposes, but understanding them helps you accurately calculate your net severance payout.
  </p>

  <h2>State Income Tax</h2>
  <p>
    Most states with an income tax treat severance the same as regular wages. Nine states have no income tax at all (Alaska, Florida, Nevada, New Hampshire, South Dakota, Tennessee, Texas, Washington, Wyoming), so residents of those states owe no state tax on severance. California, New York, New Jersey, and other high-tax states apply their full marginal rates to severance income.
  </p>
  <p>
    One nuance for remote workers: if you worked in one state but are domiciled in another, the state of your physical work location typically has first taxing rights on wage income, including severance tied to that employment. This can create dual-state tax issues for employees who recently relocated. Consult a tax advisor if your situation involves multiple states.
  </p>

  <h2>Lump Sum vs. Installment Payments</h2>
  <p>
    Many separation agreements give you the option to receive severance as a lump sum or as "salary continuation" — installment payments spread over the severance period on your normal payroll schedule. The tax treatment is the same in either case, but the timing differs:
  </p>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Lump sum:</strong> All taxable in the year received. If received in the same year as months of regular salary, you may push into a higher bracket. If received in a year with little other income (e.g., you spent most of the year unemployed), the effective rate may be lower.</li>
    <li><strong>Installments:</strong> Income is spread across multiple pay periods (and potentially multiple tax years), which can soften the bracket impact and better match withholding to your actual tax liability.</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>Strategies to Reduce Your Tax Bill</h2>
  <p>
    While you can't avoid tax on severance, a few strategies can reduce the impact:
  </p>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Maximize 401(k) or 403(b) contributions:</strong> Some plans allow you to contribute severance pay to your employer-sponsored retirement plan, deferring that income from current-year tax. Confirm with your plan administrator whether severance is considered "eligible compensation" under your plan document.</li>
    <li><strong>Contribute to an HSA:</strong> If you're still covered by an HSA-eligible health plan through COBRA, you can contribute to a Health Savings Account and deduct those contributions from your taxable income.</li>
    <li><strong>Time your receipt:</strong> If you have flexibility on when to receive the severance and you expect significantly lower income next year (e.g., you're taking time off to job search), requesting installment payments that start in January of the next year can shift income into a lower-bracket year.</li>
    <li><strong>Adjust your withholding:</strong> File a new W-4 with your employer requesting additional withholding to cover the expected tax liability, avoiding an underpayment penalty at filing.</li>
  </ul>

  <p class="disclaimer">
    This guide provides general tax information and does not constitute tax advice. Tax laws change frequently and individual situations vary significantly. Consult a CPA or tax advisor regarding the tax treatment of your specific severance package.
  </p>
